<statement>
<p>nobelium-256 has a half-life of 2.91 seconds, and its decay is modeled by <m>\displaystyle{A}={A}_{{0}}{\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}^{{\frac{{t}}{{2.91}}}}</m>. If the initial amount is <m>\displaystyle{A}_{{0}}={3.3}</m>, how long will it take until only one third, approximately <m>\displaystyle{A}\approx{1.1}</m> is left? <fillin characters="5" /></p>

</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li>4.6</li></ul></p><p><m>\displaystyle{1.1}={3.3}{\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}^{{\frac{{t}}{{2.91}}}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{1}}{{3}}={\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}^{{\frac{{t}}{{2.91}}}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\ln{{\left(\frac{{1}}{{3}}\right)}}}={\left(\frac{{t}}{{2.91}}\right)}{\ln{{\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{{\ln{{\left(\frac{{1}}{{3}}\right)}}}{\left({2.91}\right)}}}{{\ln{{\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}}}}={t}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{4.6122408770986}\approx{t}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{4.6}\approx{t}</m>.</p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>

